\textbf{Question 6}

\vspace*{\baselineskip}

For each of the following sets, determine with justification their supremum and infimum, and whether the sets contain their supremum and infimum. 

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*), leftmargin=*, labelsep=0.5in]
\item $S = \left\{ x+y \ : \ 0 < x,y < 1 , \ xy=1/4 \right\}$.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(7 marks)
\end{flushright}
%
\item $T = \left\{ \frac{2m+n}{2n+m} \ : \ m,n \geq 1 \right\}$.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(7 marks)
\end{flushright}
%
\item $V = \left\{ \frac{(a+b)^2}{a^2+b^2} \ : \ a,b \in \mathbb{R}^+, \ (a,b) \neq (0,0) \right\}$.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(6 marks)
\end{flushright}
\vspace*{2\baselineskip}
\end{enumerate}

%\vspace{12pt}

\underline{Marking Guide:}\\

\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*), leftmargin=*, labelsep=0.5in]
\item From $xy=\frac14$ we have $y=\frac{1}{4x}$. 

A useful observation is that $a^2+b^2 \geq 2ab$ for any $a,b \in \mathbb{R}^+$, with equality iff $a=b$; this follows from the fact that $(a-b)^2 \geq 0$ for all $a,b \in \mathbb{R}$. Apply this yields

$$x+y = f(x) := x+\frac{1}{4x}\ge 2\sqrt{x\cdot \frac{1}{4x}}=2\sqrt{\frac14}=1,$$

with equality iff $x=\frac{1}{4x}\iff x=\frac12$, giving $y=\frac12$. Hence $\inf S=1$, attained at $(x,y)=(\tfrac12,\tfrac12)$.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(3 marks)
\end{flushright}

Compute

$$\frac54 - f(x)=\frac54 - x - \frac{1}{4x}
= -\frac{4x^2-5x+1}{4x} = -\frac{(x-1)(x-\frac14)}{x}.$$

The constraint $0<y<1$ gives us

$$0<\frac{1}{4x}<1 \iff x>\frac14.$$

For $x\in(\frac14,1)$, we have $x-1<0$ and $x-\frac14>0$, so $(x-1)(x-\frac14)<0$, hence $\frac54-f(x)>0$. Therefore

$$f(x)<\frac54\quad\text{for all }x\in\left(\frac14,1\right).$$

Also, $f(x)\to \frac54$ as $x\to(\frac14)^+$ (corresponding to $y\to 1^-$) and also as $x\to 1^-$ (corresponding to $y\to(\frac14)^+$). It follows that $\sup S  = \frac54$, but since endpoints are excluded, $\sup S$ is not attained in $S$.

\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(4 marks)
\end{flushright}
\item We first show $\tfrac12 < \frac{2m+n}{2n+m} < 2$ for all $m,n\ge 1$, both of which are demonstrated by considering the following "if and only if" equivalences:

$$\frac{2m+n}{2n+m}>\frac12
  \iff 2(2m+n)>2n+m
  \iff 4m+2n>2n+m
  \iff 3m>0,$$

$$\frac{2m+n}{2n+m}<2
  \iff 2m+n<2(2n+m)=4n+2m
  \iff n<4n
  \iff 3n>0.$$

So every element of $T$ lies in $(\tfrac12,2)$.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(3 marks)
\end{flushright}

Fix $n=1$. We have

$$\frac{2m+1}{m+2}=2-\frac{3}{m+2}.$$

This shows that no element of $T$ can be equal $2$, and it also shows that $\sup T = 2$ because

$$\lim_{m \to \infty} \left( 2-\frac{3}{m+2} \right) = 2.$$

Fix $m=1$. We have

$$\frac{n+2}{2n+1}=\frac12+\frac{3}{2(2n+1)}$$

This shows that no element of $T$ can be equal $1/2$, and it also shows that $\inf T = 1/2$ because

$$\lim_{n \to \infty} \left( \frac12+\frac{3}{2(2n+1)} \right) = 1/2.$$
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(4 marks)
\end{flushright}
\item Write

$$\frac{(a+b)^2}{a^2+b^2}=\frac{a^2+2ab+b^2}{a^2+b^2}=1+\frac{2ab}{a^2+b^2}.$$

Since $a,b > 0$, we have

$$1+\frac{2ab}{a^2+b^2} > 1.$$

So $\inf V\ge 1$.

Also, taking $b\to 0^+$ with $a>0$ fixed gives

$$\lim_{b \to 0^+} \left[ \frac{(a+b)^2}{a^2+b^2} \right] = \frac{a^2}{a^2}=1,$$

so values can be made arbitrarily close to $1$ but can never be $1$. Therefore

$$\inf V = 1$$

and the set $V$ does not contain its infimum.
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(3 marks)
\end{flushright}

Using $a^2+b^2 \geq 2ab$ for all $a,b \in \mathbb{R}$, we obtain

$$(a+b)^2 \leq 2(a^2+b^2).$$

Thus

$$\frac{(a+b)^2}{a^2+b^2}\le 2,$$

so $\sup V\le 2$. Equality occurs when $a=b$. Hence 

$$\sup V=2,$$

and it is attained when $a=b$ (for instance, $a=b=1$).
\vspace*{-\baselineskip}
\begin{flushright}
(3 marks)
\end{flushright}
\end{enumerate}
